    "contents" : "---\ntitle: \"R Programming\"\nsubtitle: \"Advanced Graphics with ggplot\"\nauthor: | \n  | Brad Boehmke, Ph.D.\noutput: \n  ioslides_presentation:\n    logo: images/uc_logo2.png\n    widescreen: true\n    smaller: true\n    transition: 0.01\n---\n\n\n# Key Things to Remember\n\n## What to Remember from this Section\n\nEvery ggplot2 plot has three key components:\n\n1. Data\n2. A set of aesthetic mappings between variables in the data and visual\nproperties\n3. At least one layer which describes how to render each observation. Layers\nare usually created with a geom function.\n\n\n# GR&A | That means grounds rules & assumptions\n\n## R package used...\n\n<br><br><br>\n\n<center>\n<font size=\"7\" color=\"#d6d6d6\">\ninstall.packages(\"ggplot2\")\n</font>\n</center>\n\n<br>\n\n<center>\n<font size=\"7\">\nlibrary(ggplot2)\n</font>\n</center>\n\n<br><br><br><br>\n\n<center>\n<font size=\"6\">\nWe'll use the built-in `mpg` data set\n</font>\n</center>\n\n```{r, echo=FALSE, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}\nlibrary(ggplot2)\n```\n\n\n\n# Fundamentals of ggplot\n\n## First Layer is, well, boring\n\n```{r, eval=FALSE}\n# equivalent syntax\nggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy))\nggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy))\n```\n\n\n```{r, fig.align='center', echo=FALSE, fig.height=4}\nggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy))\n```\n\n## Let's Add Geoms\n\nTo display the data we need to tell ggplot what to draw\n\n-----------------       ----------------------------------     \n`geom_histogram()`      histogram\n`geom_freqpoly()`       frequency polygon\n`geom_bar()`            bar chart\n`geom_point()`          scatter plot\n`geom_line()`           line chart\n`geom_boxplot()`        boxplot\n-----------------       ----------------------------------\n\n<br>\n\nCheck out all the available geoms at [docs.ggplot2.org/current](docs.ggplot2.org/current)\n\n# Univariate Geoms\n\n## Histogram & Frequency Polygons\n\n```{r, eval=FALSE}\nggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = hwy)) +\n        geom_histogram()\n\nggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = hwy)) +\n        geom_freqpoly()\n```\n\n```{r, echo=FALSE, fig.align='center', fig.width=10, fig.height=3, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}\np1 <- ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = hwy)) +\n        geom_histogram()\n\np2 <- ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = hwy)) +\n        geom_freqpoly()\n\nlibrary(gridExtra)\ngrid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2)\n```\n\n## Histogram & Frequency Polygons\n```{r, eval=FALSE}\nggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = hwy)) +\n        geom_histogram(bins = 25, color = \"grey30\", fill = \"white\")\n\nggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = hwy)) +\n        geom_freqpoly(bins = 25, color = \"blue\")\n```\n\n```{r, echo=FALSE, fig.align='center', fig.width=10, fig.height=3, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}\np1 <- ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = hwy)) +\n        geom_histogram(bins = 25, color = \"grey30\", fill = \"white\")\n\np2 <- ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = hwy)) +\n        geom_freqpoly(bins = 25, color = \"blue\")\n\nlibrary(gridExtra)\ngrid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2)\n```\n\n\n## Bar Chart\n```{r, eval=FALSE}\nggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = class)) +\n        geom_bar()\n\nggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = cyl)) +\n        geom_bar()\n\nggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = factor(cyl))) +\n        geom_bar()\n```\n\n```{r, echo=FALSE, fig.align='center', fig.width=10, fig.height=3, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}\np1 <- ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = class)) +\n        geom_bar()\n\np2 <- ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = cyl)) +\n        geom_bar()\n\np3 <- ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = factor(cyl))) +\n        geom_bar()\n\ngrid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, ncol = 3)\n```\n\n\n## Your Turn\n\n<br>\n\n<font size=\"6\">\nImport the `facebook.tsv` file in the data folder\n</font>\n\n<br>\n\n<blockquote>\n<font size=\"6\">\n1. Assess the distribution of age. What does this tell you?\n</font>\n</blockquote>\n\n<br>\n\n<blockquote>\n<font size=\"6\">\n2. Assess the distribution of age with a boxplot. What does this tell you?\n</font>\n</blockquote>\n\n<br>\n\n<blockquote>\n<font size=\"6\">\n3. Assess the frequency of each gender. What does this tell you?\n</font>\n</blockquote>\n\n\n## Solution\n\n# Bivariate Geoms\n\n\n\n# Multivariate Capabilities\n\n\n\n",
